1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,127
Il Giappone è un paese che ha influenzato
il mondo in così tanti modi.

2
00:00:04,127 --> 00:00:07,313
Il loro cibo,
la loro tecnologia,

3
00:00:07,313 --> 00:00:09,466
o il loro contributo alla cultura popolare

4
00:00:09,467 --> 00:00:10,728
come i videogiochi.

5
00:00:10,728 --> 00:00:13,224
Per molti di noi la musica dei videogiochi

6
00:00:13,224 --> 00:00:15,476
ha giocato un ruolo nella nostra crescita familiare

7
00:00:15,476 --> 00:00:18,287
più di ogni altra forma di musica al tempo

8
00:00:18,287 --> 00:00:20,81
Eppure per molti di noi,

9
00:00:20,81 --> 00:00:24,158
i compositori dietro queste melodie
senza tempo rimangono senza un volto

10
00:00:24,158 --> 00:00:26,875
DIGGIN IN THE CARTS vuole
scoprire gli uomini e le donne

11
00:00:26,875 --> 00:00:29,368
che hanno ispirato una intera generazione

12
00:00:29,368 --> 00:00:31,706
e che probabilmente hanno creato il più grande

13
00:00:31,706 --> 00:00:34,107
export di musica giapponese nel mondo.

14
00:00:34,217 --> 00:00:41,117
(chinguettio)

15
00:00:46,238 --> 00:00:51,629
All'inizio degli anni '80,
l'industria giapponese stava crescendo.

16
00:00:51,629 --> 00:00:54,211
Nel frattempo, le sale giochi
di tutto il Giappone erano vive

17
00:00:54,211 --> 00:00:56,607
con i loro bip elettronici
e le melodie semplici,

18
00:00:56,607 --> 00:00:59,54
tutto stava per cambiare però.

19
00:00:59,54 --> 00:01:02,309
Con la messa in commercio del NES, nel 1983

20
00:01:02,309 --> 00:01:06,267
i videogiochi e le loro iconiche colonne sonore

21
00:01:06,267 --> 00:01:10,44
finalmente entravano nelle case di tutto il mondo.

22
00:01:10,44 --> 00:01:16,811
(rumore cittadino)

23
00:01:17,21 --> 00:01:21,595
Il primo gioco ad avere il sonoro
è stato Pong, della Atari.

24
00:01:21,595 --> 00:01:23,548
Pong, pong, pong

25
00:01:23,549 --> 00:01:25,782
Poi arrivò Space Invaders.

26
00:01:25,782 --> 00:01:28,744
♪ (Musica di Space Invaders) ♪

27
00:01:28,745 --> 00:01:31,770
Molti giapponesi hanno
un ricordo molto vivido

28
00:01:31,770 --> 00:01:34,520
dei suoni di Space Invaders.

29
00:01:34,520 --> 00:01:36,937
Chiameresti questa una melodia?

30
00:01:36,937 --> 00:01:39,374
duh, duh, duh, duh,
duh, duh, duh, duh,

31
00:01:39,374 --> 00:01:41,696
Forse la chiameresti una melodia,

32
00:01:41,697 --> 00:01:43,670
o forse è solo un effetto sonoro.

33
00:01:43,670 --> 00:01:44,768
(Ride)

34
00:01:44,768 --> 00:01:48,989
♪ (suoni e rumori da 
Space Invaders) ♪

35
00:01:49,59 --> 00:01:53,436
Space invaders fu un grande successo al tempo

36
00:01:53,436 --> 00:01:57,497
c'erano sale giochi 
che avevano solo Space Invaders

37
00:01:57,497 --> 00:02:00,409
chiamate Invader House.

38
00:02:00,409 --> 00:02:03,923
Il successo di Space Invaders fu così grande

39
00:02:03,923 --> 00:02:08,747
che ci fù pure la diceria delle
monete da 100¥ che scarseggiavano.

40
00:02:08,747 --> 00:02:16,203
♪ (Musica da Rally X) ♪

41
00:02:16,573 --> 00:02:19,639
Qualche tempo dopo, uscì Rally X

42
00:02:19,649 --> 00:02:22,151
della Namco.

43
00:02:22,151 --> 00:02:27,165
Fu il primo gioco ad avere una musica
che suonava di continuo in sottofondo.

44
00:02:27,165 --> 00:02:34,90
Non c'è niente come loro per i giapponesi,

45
00:02:34,91 --> 00:02:37,969
Namco è come se fosse il padrino della game music.

46
00:02:38,49 --> 00:02:46,697
♪ (Musica di Pac-Man) ♪

47
00:02:47,707 --> 00:02:50,422
Potevi andare in qualsiasi sala giochi dell'epoca

48
00:02:50,422 --> 00:02:52,947
che trovavi la melodia di Pac-Man ovunque.

49
00:02:52,947 --> 00:02:55,992
La gente di tutto il mondo ha giocato a Pac-Man

50
00:02:55,992 --> 00:02:59,136
Chiunque ha remixato Pac-Man.

51
00:02:59,956 --> 00:03:02,750
(Ride)

52
00:03:02,750 --> 00:03:04,965
Aspetta, dammi 2 secondi.

53
00:03:04,965 --> 00:03:07,530
Se non è qui, so esattamente dov'è...

54
00:03:07,530 --> 00:03:10,43
Pac-Man...
Quell'intro all'inizio

55
00:03:10,43 --> 00:03:12,448
mi ricorda la voglia disperata

56
00:03:12,448 --> 00:03:14,553
di risparmiare abbastanza pezzi da 20 cent

57
00:03:14,553 --> 00:03:16,743
per giocarli al fish'n'chip,

58
00:03:16,743 --> 00:03:19,291
oppure allo 'spacies parlour'
come lo chiamiamo in Nuova Zelanda

59
00:03:19,291 --> 00:03:20,649
(Ride)

60
00:03:20,649 --> 00:03:23,307
Ci sono quasi...

61
00:03:23,388 --> 00:03:26,496
Quella roba 8-bit è come un virus,
è infetta...

62
00:03:26,496 --> 00:03:29,800
è uscito da questo piccolo mondo
dei giochi 8-bit

63
00:03:29,800 --> 00:03:33,395
E si è espanso per infettare
così tanti generi differenti.

64
00:03:33,395 --> 00:03:37,505
Che si tratti di Hip-Hop,
Dubstep, Grime, Techno...

65
00:03:37,505 --> 00:03:40,518
Adesso pure il footwork

66
00:03:40,518 --> 00:03:44,211
♪ (Remix della melodia di Pac-Man) ♪

67
00:03:44,211 --> 00:03:47,626
Probabilmente senza che molti di noi
ragazzini Hip-Hop sapessero

68
00:03:47,626 --> 00:03:50,125
che questa musica 8-bit, 16-bit

69
00:03:50,125 --> 00:03:52,575
in qualche modo ci ha influenzato tutti,

70
00:03:52,575 --> 00:03:54,718
perchè tutti abbiamo giocati ai videogiochi.

71
00:03:54,718 --> 00:03:57,5
Dovevi aver giocato ai videogiochi,
non era uno scherzo.

72
00:03:57,5 --> 00:03:58,582
♪ (Remix della melodia di Pac-Man) ♪

73
00:03:58,582 --> 00:04:00,140
♪ ("Game Over" da Pac-Man) ♪

74
00:04:00,140 --> 00:04:03,136
All'epoca Namco, come veniva chiamata allora,

75
00:04:03,136 --> 00:04:07,428
aveva una strabiliante compositrice
di nome Junko Ozawa.

76
00:04:07,428 --> 00:04:10,676
Credo sia stata la persona che ha gettato le basi

77
00:04:10,676 --> 00:04:14,160
per quello che è diventato noto come il suono Namco.

78
00:04:14,420 --> 00:04:21,954
♪ (Musica di Gaplus) ♪

79
00:04:28,494 --> 00:04:30,148
Mi chiamo Junko Ozawa.

80
00:04:30,148 --> 00:04:33,754
Sono entrata in Namco 30 anni fa.

81
00:04:33,754 --> 00:04:36,864
Il mio primo gioco è stato Gaplus.

82
00:04:36,864 --> 00:04:43,275
Quanto sono entrata in Namco
non sembrava di essere in una azienda.

83
00:04:43,276 --> 00:04:47,171
Sembrava più un club delle superiori.

84
00:04:47,171 --> 00:04:51,171
Era un'azienda che favoriva
il mettersi alla prova,

85
00:04:51,172 --> 00:04:56,501
non solo io, tutti quanti
si mettevano alla prova

86
00:04:56,501 --> 00:04:59,70
ed era tutto pieno di vitalità.

87
00:04:59,71 --> 00:05:01,641
♪ (NES Game music) ♪

88
00:05:01,641 --> 00:05:04,212
Al tempo,

89
00:05:04,212 --> 00:05:08,395
c'erano compagnie
che copiavano i giochi illegalmente,

90
00:05:08,395 --> 00:05:10,734
e ci fu detto di non far vedere

91
00:05:10,734 --> 00:05:12,313
che stavamo sviluppando giochi
per l'azienda.

92
00:05:12,314 --> 00:05:16,214
Dicevano che se avessi detto
a qualcuno che lavoravo per Namco

93
00:05:16,214 --> 00:05:18,65
sarei stata rapita

94
00:05:18,65 --> 00:05:23,885
ed avrebbero chiesto i progetti per un nuovo gioco
invece che un riscatto.

95
00:05:23,885 --> 00:05:25,965
Non ero sicura se fosse vero o falso.

96
00:05:26,65 --> 00:05:33,58
♪ (The Tower of Druaga) ♪

97
00:05:33,618 --> 00:05:37,268
Per il mio secondo gioco,
The Tower of Druaga, stavo studiando

98
00:05:37,268 --> 00:05:42,486
ed ho scritto la mia musica
con il mio driver audio.

99
00:05:42,486 --> 00:05:44,968
Il driver audio era

100
00:05:44,968 --> 00:05:51,994
un programma che era come uno spartito musicale
per noi mentre componevamo.

101
00:05:51,994 --> 00:05:53,136
Avevamo solo i dati

102
00:05:53,136 --> 00:05:56,81
c'era un programma che leggeva questi dati,

103
00:05:56,81 --> 00:05:58,91
e li riproduceva in forma musicale.

104
00:05:58,974 --> 00:06:05,998
♪ (THEME OF QUOX) ♪

105
00:06:14,278 --> 00:06:17,286
Lavoro per la Bandai Namco Studios
come capo del team audio.

106
00:06:17,286 --> 00:06:19,356
Mi chiamo Okubo.

107
00:06:19,356 --> 00:06:21,433
Questo è un circuito stampato con sopra

108
00:06:21,434 --> 00:06:22,890
il programma per Tower of Druaga.

109
00:06:22,890 --> 00:06:25,185
La parte che contiene il gioco è qui intorno,

110
00:06:25,185 --> 00:06:26,998
questa è la ROM del gioco

111
00:06:26,998 --> 00:06:29,649
e qui c'è la CPU per l'audio.

112
00:06:29,649 --> 00:06:33,106
Questa è il tipo di ROM
che contiene la musica del gioco

113
00:06:33,106 --> 00:06:36,609
o i dati d'onda, le forme d'onda
che Ozawa e gli altri hanno creato.

114
00:06:36,609 --> 00:06:39,126
Primo, dovevano riprodurre
la musica che avevano composto

115
00:06:39,126 --> 00:06:40,609
poi scrivere lo spartito

116
00:06:40,609 --> 00:06:44,609
e poi convertire il tutto in numeri
e programmarli al suo interno.

117
00:06:44,610 --> 00:06:48,275
E' stata un'epoca davvero dura.

118
00:06:48,465 --> 00:06:54,270
♪ (Game music) ♪

119
00:06:54,510 --> 00:06:57,553
Questa è la mia libreria di forme d'onda.

120
00:06:57,553 --> 00:07:04,17
Ne ho fatte molte così,
e ci sono tante onde differenti.

121
00:07:04,17 --> 00:07:08,371
Ogni singola onda era molto carina.

122
00:07:08,371 --> 00:07:12,15
Queste sono i miei tesori.

123
00:07:12,16 --> 00:07:15,826
Queste sono le forme d'onda
che Ozawa ha fatto per Tower of Druaga.

124
00:07:15,826 --> 00:07:18,86
Vi faccio sentire.

125
00:07:18,86 --> 00:07:20,941
Certo, l'ambiente allora
non ti permetteva di suonare

126
00:07:20,941 --> 00:07:23,133
con una tastiera, così.

127
00:07:23,134 --> 00:07:27,569
Ci sono 8 pattern
nella ROM di Tower of Druaga.

128
00:07:27,569 --> 00:07:30,388
Il primo #0 è quadrato.

129
00:07:30,897 --> 00:07:34,587
♪ (Do, Re, Mi, Fa, Sol, La, Si, Do) ♪

130
00:07:34,648 --> 00:07:36,670
E poi n°1.

131
00:07:36,740 --> 00:07:39,642
♪ (Different tones 
of Do, Re, Mi, Fa, Sol, La, Si, Do) ♪

132
00:07:39,722 --> 00:07:43,482
Penso sia il tipico suono Namco.

133
00:07:43,482 --> 00:07:44,412
♪ (Beep, beep) ♪

134
00:07:44,412 --> 00:07:45,174
Come questo.

135
00:07:45,175 --> 00:07:46,298
♪ (Beep, beep, beep) ♪

136
00:07:46,298 --> 00:07:48,361
Penso sia un bel suono.

137
00:07:48,361 --> 00:07:55,320
#6 is a sine wave. 
It's a typical sound too.

138
00:07:55,371 --> 00:08:00,798
Next is #4, which Ozawa loved.

139
00:08:00,848 --> 00:08:04,510
♪ (Beep, beep. C, D, E, F, G, A, B, C) ♪

140
00:08:04,570 --> 00:08:09,702
♪ (Namcòs NES Game music) ♪

141
00:08:09,762 --> 00:08:13,28
The appeal of the 8-bit sound is

142
00:08:13,28 --> 00:08:15,847
that it can't be done any other way.

143
00:08:15,847 --> 00:08:19,376
The cheapness of it is very unique.

144
00:08:19,377 --> 00:08:24,12
A Stradivarius violin is amazing,

145
00:08:24,12 --> 00:08:27,247
but extreme cheapness and simplicity

146
00:08:27,247 --> 00:08:30,781
can't be produced by any instrument.

147
00:08:30,781 --> 00:08:35,131
I think both of them are
individual instruments

148
00:08:35,131 --> 00:08:38,10
that I really love.

149
00:08:38,221 --> 00:08:42,1
♪ (NES Game music) ♪

150
00:08:42,71 --> 00:08:44,401
The NES came out in 1983.

151
00:08:44,401 --> 00:08:47,314
There was an NES craze all over Japan.

152
00:08:47,314 --> 00:08:54,141
At the time, I was amazed
we could play arcade games at home.

153
00:08:54,145 --> 00:08:57,6
It was a big deal, it was just like wow!

154
00:08:57,6 --> 00:08:59,131
Nintendo’s making a home console.

155
00:08:59,131 --> 00:09:03,545
Yeah, you couldn’t front on Nintendo
back then, everybody had one.

156
00:09:03,546 --> 00:09:06,946
I remember blowing on
the cartridges do get ‘em

157
00:09:06,946 --> 00:09:08,991
to work when it wasn’t working.

158
00:09:08,991 --> 00:09:11,400
But Nintendo was dope, that was dope.

159
00:09:11,400 --> 00:09:15,487
The music of early Nintendo was sick,
the electronic sound of it.

160
00:09:15,487 --> 00:09:18,197
The rhythms of it, it had a lot of
rhythms, the drums,

161
00:09:18,197 --> 00:09:20,284
even the drums were ill in that.

162
00:09:20,284 --> 00:09:23,231
They were really smart
with the kinds of loops that they made,

163
00:09:23,231 --> 00:09:25,326
because they knew you were
gonna be listening to them

164
00:09:25,326 --> 00:09:26,908
for hours & hours & hours.

165
00:09:26,908 --> 00:09:29,830
Hip-Tanaka is kinda like THE GUY,

166
00:09:29,830 --> 00:09:34,60
I guess, when it comes to
incredible chip music

167
00:09:34,60 --> 00:09:39,36
Hirokazu Tanaka was originally
a musician in a Reggae Band

168
00:09:39,36 --> 00:09:41,444
but after joining Nintendo
he was creating hardware too.

169
00:09:41,445 --> 00:09:44,85
He was the first person to be in charge of

170
00:09:44,85 --> 00:09:46,445
game music composition for Nintendo.

171
00:09:46,445 --> 00:09:52,735
He worked on various titles like
Balloon Fight and Kid Icarus.

172
00:09:52,735 --> 00:09:58,65
He was deeply involved in hardware design 
for the NES sound chip,

173
00:09:58,65 --> 00:10:02,277
and went onto designing
Game Boy sound hardware too.

174
00:10:02,277 --> 00:10:06,188
He’s kinda of like this idol guy.

175
00:10:06,188 --> 00:10:08,181
There’s a lot of them – but he’s THE GUY.

176
00:10:08,541 --> 00:10:16,184
♪ (NES Game music) ♪

177
00:10:24,724 --> 00:10:26,938
My name is Hirokazu Tanaka.

178
00:10:26,938 --> 00:10:30,965
I joined a company called Nintendo in 1980.

179
00:10:30,965 --> 00:10:34,199
Since then ìve mainly been involved
in game hardware

180
00:10:34,199 --> 00:10:36,233
and music composition.

181
00:10:36,233 --> 00:10:39,111
Recently ìve been working on Pokemon

182
00:10:39,111 --> 00:10:41,947
the anime, the movie theme song and so on.

183
00:10:42,7 --> 00:10:48,193
♪ (NES Game music) ♪

184
00:10:48,273 --> 00:10:49,470
This is TOFUKU-JI Temple.

185
00:10:49,470 --> 00:10:53,460
When I joined Nintendo,
I used to hang out here every day.

186
00:10:53,460 --> 00:10:57,330
It feels relaxing around here.
It's peaceful.

187
00:10:57,500 --> 00:11:01,440
♪ (Game music continues) ♪

188
00:11:01,530 --> 00:11:03,540
When I joined Nintendo

189
00:11:03,541 --> 00:11:05,566
I was making sound effects

190
00:11:05,566 --> 00:11:07,788
but it wasn't like making them
on a computer nowadays.

191
00:11:07,788 --> 00:11:12,400
it was kind of like making
an old synthesizer

192
00:11:12,400 --> 00:11:15,20
With repeated trial and error

193
00:11:15,20 --> 00:11:17,936
I lined up a soldering iron
and a bunch of components

194
00:11:17,936 --> 00:11:20,111
while doing cut & try

195
00:11:20,111 --> 00:11:21,282
and that's how I made sounds.

196
00:11:21,342 --> 00:11:23,833
♪ (NES Game music) ♪

197
00:11:23,903 --> 00:11:27,235
Before the NES came out, 
with arcade games

198
00:11:27,235 --> 00:11:30,81
I made all of the sound chips myself,

199
00:11:30,81 --> 00:11:34,336
but with the NES 
there was a sound chip inside

200
00:11:34,336 --> 00:11:37,738
so I had to control that 
with the CPU instead

201
00:11:37,738 --> 00:11:39,733
so, it became easier to create

202
00:11:39,733 --> 00:11:42,93
and I could freely use 3 sounds and noise

203
00:11:42,93 --> 00:11:44,819
it was a lot of fun.

204
00:11:44,880 --> 00:11:48,917
♪ (NES Game music) ♪

205
00:11:48,987 --> 00:11:51,853
I got into reggae in my late teens.

206
00:11:51,854 --> 00:11:53,527
Bob Marley was alive at the time

207
00:11:53,527 --> 00:11:58,371
and I like the bass of a bass player

208
00:11:58,415 --> 00:12:00,448
named Jah Wobble from a band called P.I.L.

209
00:12:00,478 --> 00:12:03,69
This place is called Rub A Dub

210
00:12:03,118 --> 00:12:07,552
A few years after I joined Nintendo,
from about 1986 or '87

211
00:12:07,552 --> 00:12:12,235
I came to this place
a couple of times a week to drink beer

212
00:12:12,235 --> 00:12:16,440
and enjoy reggae before going home.

213
00:12:16,799 --> 00:12:20,601
Just seeing the R from Reggae
would make my heart race

214
00:12:20,601 --> 00:12:24,53
When I saw the three colours red,
yellow and green around town

215
00:12:24,53 --> 00:12:28,126
ìd think 'Reggae!'
That's how much I loved it.

216
00:12:28,196 --> 00:12:33,819
♪ (NES Game music) ♪

217
00:12:33,909 --> 00:12:36,273
The games Balloon Fight 
and Wrecking Crew

218
00:12:36,273 --> 00:12:39,773
had the rhythm of Sly Dunbar.

219
00:12:39,773 --> 00:12:45,223
I liked the intricacy of
Sly Dunbar's rhythm back then

220
00:12:45,228 --> 00:12:48,787
and it's always stayed with me.

221
00:12:48,788 --> 00:12:52,596
So when I made game music,
his rhythm came through as is.

222
00:12:52,706 --> 00:13:00,154
♪ (Game music) ♪

223
00:13:00,324 --> 00:13:04,771
I was responsible for
the Game Boy sound chip.

224
00:13:04,772 --> 00:13:09,42
We had to make things smaller than
the NES in many ways

225
00:13:09,42 --> 00:13:12,137
and we had to keep the cost low,
so there were various limitations.

226
00:13:12,137 --> 00:13:17,23
I had a feeling a lot of people
would play with headphones on

227
00:13:17,24 --> 00:13:21,175
so I added a lot of effects
to surprise people when they played

228
00:13:21,175 --> 00:13:25,623
I hooked it up to big speakers
like the ones in here

229
00:13:25,624 --> 00:13:29,928
and tried to imitate real rock
with a Game Boy.

230
00:13:29,928 --> 00:13:33,218
Guitar sounds are originally distorted,
and close to square waves,

231
00:13:33,218 --> 00:13:36,248
so the Game Boy is good at
doing guitar like sounds.

232
00:13:36,699 --> 00:13:44,40
♪ (Game music) ♪

233
00:13:45,470 --> 00:13:48,162
The idea that the things
